// requirements.md FR-45: wires up /usr/share/craftdeck/apt-hook so a
// package upgrade/removal that could disrupt an already-running Minecraft
// instance (its Java runtime, glibc, systemd) stops it gracefully first and
// restarts it once the apt transaction is done, instead of letting it get
// killed out from under a still-running world. See that script's own
// comment for why only Pre-Install-Pkgs (not Pre-Invoke) gets told which
// packages are actually involved.
// The "[ -x ... ] && ... || true" guard matters for Post-Invoke in
// particular: when this transaction is removing/purging craftdeck itself,
// dpkg has already deleted /usr/share/craftdeck/apt-hook (also this
// package's own file) by the time Post-Invoke runs, since apt loads this
// config's command line once up front but only executes it after all of
// dpkg's work is done -- without the guard, apt reports the whole
// transaction as failed on a plain "file not found" even though the
// removal itself succeeded (confirmed on real hardware).
DPkg::Pre-Install-Pkgs {"[ -x /usr/share/craftdeck/apt-hook ] && /usr/share/craftdeck/apt-hook pre || true";};
DPkg::Tools::Options::"[ -x /usr/share/craftdeck/apt-hook ] && /usr/share/craftdeck/apt-hook pre || true"::Version "2";
DPkg::Post-Invoke {"[ -x /usr/share/craftdeck/apt-hook ] && /usr/share/craftdeck/apt-hook post || true";};
